definitions.definition: To discover , find out ; to uncover .
To change with a specific direction , progress .
examples: Let's see how things develop and then make our decision.

definitions.definition: To progress through a sequence of stages.
examples: Isabel developed from a tropical depression to a tropical storm to a hurricane.   An embryo develops into a fetus and then into an infant.

definitions.definition: To advance; to further; to promote the growth of.

examples: I need to develop a plan for the next three weeks.

definitions.definition: To bring out images latent in photographic film .
examples: Please develop this roll of film.

definitions.definition: To acquire something usually over a period of time.
examples: I have been in England enough to develop a British accent.
You will develop calluses if you play the cello.
I need to develop my white-square bishop.

definitions.definition: To cause a ball to become more open and available to be played on later. Usually by moving it away from the cushion, or by opening a pack .
To change the form of (an algebraic expression , etc.) by executing certain indicated operations without changing the value .

main_definition: ( transitive or impersonal , now rare ) To discover , find out ; to uncover .
secondary_definitions: ( intransitive ) To change with a specific direction , progress .
( ambitransitive ) To progress through a sequence of stages.
( transitive ) To advance; to further; to promote the growth of.
( transitive ) To bring out images latent in photographic film .
( transitive ) To acquire something usually over a period of time.
( chess , transitive ) To place one's pieces actively .
( snooker , pool ) To cause a ball to become more open and available to be played on later. Usually by moving it away from the cushion, or by opening a pack .
( mathematics ) To change the form of (an algebraic expression , etc.) by executing certain indicated operations without changing the value .
